Indicator: Rate of Laboratory Confirmed Infections Caused by Shiga Toxin-Producing E-Coli (Per 100,000 people)
BCHC Requested Methodology: Rate of lab-confirmed infections caused by Shiga Toxin-Producing E-Coli per 100,000 population using 2010 US Census figures.
Source: County of San Diego, Health and Human Services Agency, Public Health Services, Epidemiology and Immunizations Services Branch; January, 2018; SANDAG Current Population Estimates, Received May 2017.
Methods: Annual case counts are grouped by CDC disease year, following the schema of CDC disease weeks, which do not necessarily reflect the calendar year. Cases are grouped into year on the basis of the earliest of the following dates: onset date, laboratory specimen collection date, diagnosis date, death date, date report was received. Rates are calculated per 100,000 population using the appropriate population stratifications and year population estimates as received by the San Diego Association of Governments (SANDAG) which is our county's official census holder.
Notes: Shiga toxin-Producing E. coli (including O157) confirmed cases only. Cases include non-residents and those of unknown residence who received diagnosis while in the county.

Methods: Annual case counts are grouped by CDC disease year, following the schema of CDC disease weeks, which do not necessarily reflect the calendar year. Cases are grouped into year on the basis of the earliest of the following dates: onset date, laboratory specimen collection date, diagnosis date, death date, date report was received. Rates are calculated per 100,000 population using the appropriate population stratifications and year population estimates as received by the San Diego Association of Governments (SANDAG) which is our county's official census holder.
Notes: Shiga toxin-Producing E. coli (including O157) confirmed cases only. Cases include non-residents and those of unknown residence who received diagnosis while in the county.

Methods: Annual case counts are grouped by CDC disease year, following the schema of CDC disease weeks, which do not necessarily reflect the calendar year.
